      %details(open="")
        %summary Sequential Circuits
        %section
          %img.logo.round(src="images/pyaiger.svg" loading="lazy")/
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/py-aiger")
              pyAiger:

            A python library for convenient modeling/ manipulation
            of sequential circuits, combinatorial circuits, and
            boolean expressions represented as <b>(A)nd</b>
            & <b>(I)nverter</b> <b>(G)ates</b> (AIGs). Co-developed
            with <a href="https://people.eecs.berkeley.edu/~rabe/">Markus
            N. Rabe</a>.

        %section
          %img.logo.round(src="images/pyaiger-bv.svg" loading="lazy")/
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/py-aiger-bv")
              pyAiger-BV:

            Word Level (bitvector) abstractions on top of <a
            href="https://github.com/mvcisback/py-aiger">pyAiger</a>.
            Co-developed with <a href="https://people.eecs.berkeley.edu/~rabe/">
            Markus N. Rabe</a>.

        %p
          There are <a href="https://github.com/mvcisback/py-aiger#ecosystem">
          a number of other projects</a> that I have spawned off the
          py-aiger code base for supporting bdds, SAT solvers, past
          tense LTL, gridworlds, and conversion to and from DFAs.

      %details
        %summary Time-Series

        %section
          %img#mtl.logo.wide(src="images/mtl_logo.png" loading="lazy")/
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/py-metric-temporal-logic")
              py-Metric-Temporal-Logic:

            Python library for working with Metric Temporal Logic
            (MTL). Metric Temporal Logic is an extension of Linear
            Temporal Logic (LTL) for specifying properties over time
            series.

        %section
          %img.logo(loading="lazy" src="images/discretesignals_logo.svg")/
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/discretesignals")
              DiscreteSignals:

            A Python embedded domain specific language for modeling
            and manipulating discrete time signals. The key
            distinction between many other timeseries libraries is the
            lightweight encoding of non-uniform time steps. This
            abstraction made implementing the py-Metric-Temporal-Logic
            library much easier.

      %details
        %summary Specification Inference
        
        %section
          %p 
            <a href="https://github.com/mvcisback/DISS">
            Demonstration Informed Specification Search
            (DISS)</a>: a tool for learning "Boolean Task Specifications", in the form
            of automata or logic, from demonstrations.
        %section
          %img.logo(loading="lazy" src="images/sifd.svg")/
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/gridworld-visualizer")
              Gridworld Visualizer:

            Python Code for visualizing gridworlds used in my research

        %section
          %img.logo(loading="lazy" src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mvcisback/monotone-bipartition/master/assets/bipartition.svg?sanitize=true")/
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/monotone-bipartition")
              Monotone Bipartition:

            This library enable manipulating and comparing implicitly
            defined monotone bipartitions on the unit box using
            adaptive mesh refinement.
            %br/
            Inspired by <a href="https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01556243/">
            Maler, Oded. "Learning Monotone Partitions of Partially-Ordered Domains
            (Work in Progress)." (2017).</a> and the main work horse our series of
            papers on Logical Lens and Logical Clustering.

        %section
          %img.logo.wide(loading="lazy" src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mvcisback/LogicalLens/master/assets/bipartition.svg?sanitize=true")/
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/LogicalLens")
              Logical Lens:0

            Implementation of Logical Lens algorithm for (1) using a
            parametric specification to map data to an abstract
            boundary and (2) compute the induced "Logical Distance"
            between data w.r.t. a parametric specification.

      %details
        %summary Automata

        %section
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/dfa")
              DFA:

            A simple python implementation of a Deterministic Finite
            Automata and Moore Machines. Notable features include
            implicit/lazy definitions, immutable/frozen design, and
            hashability.

        %section
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/lstar")
              lstar:

            Python implementation of the discriminant tree for
            learning DFA and Moore Machines from membership and
            equivalence queries. Supports a co-routine API for
            interfacing with other learning algorithms. Works well
            with my dfa library :)

        %section
          %p
            %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/dfa-identify")
              dfa-identify:

            Python implementation of SAT based Deterministic Finite Automata
            identification from a set of accepting and rejecting strings.


      %details
        %summary Other

        %p
          %a(href="https://github.com/mvcisback/pyLazyTree")
            Lazy Tree:

          Python library for manipulating infinite trees. Used in a
          number of my libraries. For example, the adaptive
          mesh-refinement in monotone-bipartition and the
          counterexample search tree in lstar.

          Useful when a problem can be framed as a search on infinite trees
          which themselves may be functions of infinite trees.

    
